      "By compactness of `[0, 2π]`, there exists a convergent subsequence `y_n → y ∈ [0, 2π]`.\n   - But `g` is continuous on `[0, 2π]`, so `g y_n → g y`, and thus `g y = f a`.\n   - But `y_n ∈ (0, 2π]`, so if `y = 0`, then `y_n → 0+`, but `g y_n → g(0)` (since `g` is continuous at `0`).\n   - Thus, `g(0) = f a`, but then for `y` near `0`, `‖f a - g y‖ ≈ ‖g(0) - g y‖` which is small.\n   - But perhaps in this case, `y = 0`, and `g 0 = f a`, and `g y ≈ g(0) + g'(0)y` for small `y > 0`.\n\nBut we don't need all this detail because in Lean, `Real.log ‖f a - g y‖ = 0` when `g y = f a`, and otherwise it is `Real.log (positive)`.\n\nBut this approach is too complicated, so let's instead use the fact that in Lean, `Real.log x` is bounded above for `x ∈ (0, ∞)`.\n\nActually, no. \n\nA better approach: \n\n1. The function `y ↦ g y` is analytic on `(0, 2π]` (because it's analytic on a neighborhood of each point in `(0, 2π]`).\n   - Wait no: `AnalyticOnNhd ℝ g univ` means that for every `x : ℝ`, there exists an open ball around `x` where `g` is analytic (as a function from `ℝ` to `ℂ`). \n   - But this implies that `g` is analytic as a function from `ℝ` to `ℂ` on every compact interval (since every point has a neighborhood), but `g` is actually smooth, and in fact analytic.\n   - So `g` is continuous on `[0, 2π]`.\n2. Therefore, `y ↦ ‖f a - g y‖` is continuous on `(0, 2π]`, and bounded if we can include the endpoint `0`.\n   - But we can't because the interval is `(0, 2π]`.\n   - But perhaps we can extend `g` to `[0, 2π]` by continuity.\n3. But perhaps not: we don't know that `g` is defined at `0`, but it is analytic on a neighborhood of `0`, so it is continuous at `0`.\n\nActually, in Lean, `AnalyticOnNhd ℝ g univ` implies that `g` is continuous on all of `ℝ`, because for every `x : ℝ`, there exists an open ball around `x` where `g` is analytic, hence continuous. \n\nTherefore, `g` is continuous on `[0, 2π]`, and thus `y ↦ ‖f a - g y‖` is continuous on `[0, 2π]`. \n\nSo `y ↦ ‖f a - g y‖` is bounded on `[0, 2π]`, and thus on `(0, 2π]",
      "`g(y)` is bounded on `(0, 2π]`, and thus `f(a) - g(y)` is bounded, so `‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≤ M`, so `log ‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≤ log M`, where `M` is an upper bound for `‖f(a) - g(y)‖`.\n\n   Moreover, since `g(y)` is analytic on `ℝ`, it is continuous, and so `g(y)` is bounded on `(0, 2π]`, and thus `f(a) - g(y)` is bounded, but `‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≥ 0`, and `log ‖f(a) - g(y)‖` is `≥ log 0 = 0` only if `‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≥ 1`, which is not guaranteed. \n\n   Hmm, no: if `‖f(a) - g(y)‖ < 1`, then `log ‖f(a) - g(y)‖ < 0`.\n\n   However, because `g(y)` is bounded on `(0, 2π]`, say by `B`, then `‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≤ ‖f(a)‖ + B`, and `‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≥ | ‖f(a)‖ - B |`. \n\n   However, we can't say much more because if `f(a)` is fixed but large, and `g(y)` is small, then `‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≈ ‖f(a)‖`, and `log ‖f(a) - g(y)‖ ≈ log ‖f(a)‖",
